              "Create a prompt that directs the AI to generate insights about the issue above. After you craft your prompt, record it in the space below.": "You are an unbiased policy advisor helping a high school decide whether to ban all smartphones during school hours. Generate balanced insights and practical options.\n\t1.\tClarify the decision: Define what “ban all smartphones” could mean (e.g., off and stored, allowed at lunch only, teacher-permitted use, emergency exceptions) and what counts as “school hours.”\n\t2.\tStakeholder impacts: Analyze pros/cons for students (learning, focus, mental health, social life), teachers (classroom management, instruction), parents (communication, safety), and the school (discipline, equity).\n\t3.\tEvidence-based reasoning (no fake citations): Summarize typical findings from credible research areas (attention, multitasking, cyberbullying, sleep, academic outcomes), but don’t invent study names or statistics.\n\t4.\tEquity and safety: Discuss issues like students who need phones for medical reasons, translation, accessibility, or after-school jobs; and how emergencies would be handled.\n\t5.\tImplementation plan: Provide 3 policy models (strict ban / partial restriction / guided use) with clear rules, enforcement methods, consequences, and ways to avoid unfair punishment.\n\t6.\tRisks & unintended consequences: Predict what could go wrong (hidden use, teacher conflict, loss/theft, student anxiety) and how to mitigate it.\n\t7.\tRecommendation framework: Propose criteria to evaluate success (learning outcomes, behavior incidents, bullying reports, student well-being), plus a 3-month pilot plan and feedback process.\n\nOutput in a structured format with headings, bullet points, and a short conclusion that compares the options.",
              "Please revise your prompt and record it in the space below.": "Act as a neutral education policy analyst. Help me evaluate the question: “Should a high school ban all smartphones during school hours?” I need a balanced, practical, and well-structured analysis I can use for a school debate essay.\n\nContext (assume): A typical public high school (ages 14–18). Many students use phones for messaging, photos, music, and occasional learning apps. The school worries about distraction, cheating, cyberbullying, and mental health, but parents also want easy contact for safety.\n\nYour tasks:\n\t1.\tDefine the policy options precisely\n\n\t•\tExplain at least 4 models:\n\t•\tFull ban (phones off + stored all day)\n\t•\tPartial ban (allowed during lunch/breaks only)\n\t•\t“Teacher-permitted” use (only when a teacher requests it)\n\t•\t“Guided use” policy (phones allowed but tightly regulated)\n\t•\tFor each model, list: what’s allowed, what’s not, exceptions (medical/accessibility/emergency), and how “school hours” is defined.\n\n\t2.\tCompare benefits and harms using reasoning grounded in research areas\n\n\t•\tDiscuss likely effects on: attention/learning, classroom behavior, academic integrity, social dynamics, cyberbullying, stress/anxiety, and teacher workload.\n\t•\tDo not invent study titles, authors, or statistics. If you mention evidence, describe it generally (e.g., “research often finds…”).\n\n\t3.\tStakeholder analysis\n\n\t•\tStudents, teachers, administrators, and parents: top 3 concerns each + what “success” looks like for them.\n\n\t4.\tEquity, accessibility, and safety\n\n\t•\tAddress students who need phones for health (e.g., diabetes monitoring), translation, disability accommodations, or family responsibilities.\n\t•\tPropose an emergency communication plan that works even with restrictions.\n\n\t5.\tImplementation & enforcement design\n\n\t•\tGive realistic enforcement methods (e.g., phone lockers, sealed pouches, classroom caddies) and compare them on cost, fairness, privacy, and practicality.\n\t•\tProvide a discipline approach that minimizes conflict and avoids punishing students unevenly.\n\n\t6.\tUnintended consequences + mitigation\n\n\t•\tPredict at least 5 likely “workarounds” or negative side effects and how to reduce them.\n\n\t7.\tDecision support\n\n\t•\tProvide a simple scoring matrix (criteria + weights) that a principal could use to choose a policy.\n\t•\tEnd with a short recommendation that names the best option under the assumed context, and also notes what conditions would change that recommendation.\n\nOutput format: Use clear headings, bullet points, and a final 120–150 word conclusion I can paste into an essay.",
              "When I started writing my prompt, I had a clear and specific goal for what I wanted the AI to accomplish.": "3 - Neutral",
              "While writing my prompt, I thought about how different wording might change the way the AI reasons or responds.": "4 - Agree",
