              "Refine your prompt and record it in the space below.": "GRASP Prompt： Should a high school ban all smartphones during school hours?\n\nGoal (What I want you to do):\nAnalyze and compare whether a high school should ban all smartphones during school hours, and give realistic policy recommendations and an implementation plan.\n\nRole (Who you are):\nAct as a neutral school policy advisor with knowledge of education research and student well-being.\n\nAudience (Who this is for):\nWrite for a school decision group: the principal, teachers, student council representatives, and parents.\n\nStrategy for Reasoning (How you should think):\n\t•\tStart by defining what “ban all smartphones” could mean and list multiple policy options (not just yes/no).\n\t•\tUse evidence-informed reasoning: describe common research findings in general terms without inventing statistics or fake citations.\n\t•\tEvaluate trade-offs with clear criteria (learning focus, safety, fairness, mental health, enforceability, cost).\n\t•\tIdentify risks and unintended consequences, then propose mitigations.\n\t•\tEnd with a clear recommendation under the given assumptions and explain what information could change the decision.\n\nPerspective (Angles to consider):\n\t•\tLearning & attention vs. digital literacy & responsible use\n\t•\tStudent mental health & social life vs. discipline & academic integrity (cheating)\n\t•\tSafety & emergency communication vs. privacy & surveillance concerns\n\t•\tEquity & accessibility (medical needs, disability accommodations, translation) vs. consistent rules for all\n\nOutput requirements:\nProvide:\n\t1.\t3–4 policy models with rules and exceptions\n\t2.\tPros/cons for each stakeholder group\n\t3.\tAn enforcement approach that is fair and practical\n\t4.\tA simple scoring table to compare options\n\t5.\tA final 120–150 word conclusion suitable for a debate essay",
